50|$|When {{displaying}} <b>the</b> US <b>flag,</b> it is customary {{for it to}} {{be above}} a state's flag when flown on the same pole. When flown separately, a state's flag may be at the same height as <b>the</b> US <b>flag,</b> with <b>the</b> US <b>flag</b> to <b>the</b> left of <b>the</b> state <b>flag,</b> from <b>the</b> perspective of the viewer. When flown with several state <b>flags,</b> <b>the</b> US <b>flag</b> should be at the same height and to <b>the</b> <b>flag's</b> own right (viewer's left), or at the center of and higher than a grouping of state <b>flags.</b> <b>The</b> idea that only the Texas and Hawaii flags—having been <b>the</b> national <b>flags</b> of <b>the</b> Republic of Texas and the Kingdom of Hawaii—may be flown at an equal height to <b>the</b> US <b>flag</b> is a legend. In fact, any other flag may be flown at an equal height to <b>the</b> US <b>flag</b> provided <b>the</b> US <b>flag</b> is at <b>the</b> leftmost staff {{from the perspective of the}} viewer.|$|R
